{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_gabardine_ver01/data/sn87065163/00199916804/1908042101/0320.xml":{"full_text":"MILL OWNERS\nHarvic Jordan Say* Slow Buying of\nCotton i* Playing Into the\nHands of Speculators.\nEFFORT TO SHUT DOWN\nHAS FAILED DISMALLY\nDeclare* Trade Condition* Are Im\nproving, Unemployed Are Being Put\nto Work, and Present Lull Cannot\nLast Long.\n^.tlanta, Ga., April 20.\u2014That the\ndecline in the price of spot cotton,\nrather than a general trade depres\nsion, la responsible for the distress\nof mill owners throughout the coun\ntry, is the view taken by President\nHarvie ford an, of the Southern Cot\nton association. He declares that as\nprices descend, the fobbing trade\ndemands concessions in the price of\njam and fabrics. The mill find ihem\nwith accumulated stocks,\nselves\nmanufactured when cotton was high,\nwhich they don't care to sell at prices\nlower than those several months\nback. Says Mr. Jordan:\n\"For several months prior to April\nfirst, the spinning industry in New\nEngland and the south was very\nA goodly number\nmuch disturbed,\nof mills in Massachusetts, the Caro\nUnas and Georgia were forced to go\non short time in order to prevent the\naccumulation of yams and manufac\ntured goods which did not find ready\nGeneral\nsale at profitable prices,\ndepression in this country, following\nfast upon jthe heels of the financial\npanic, precipitated in Wall street last\nOctober, caused a slackening up in\nthe buying power of the American\npeople. While many of the mills re\nduced their working time, a number\nof new mills, and old mills putting\nIn new machinery, have started up.\n\"Within the past two weeks\nhave heard but little talk about con\ntinued curtailment, and the efforts\nmade in both New England and the\nSouth to secure a general shut-down\ncurtailment of all the' mills for 60\nThe cotton mills\nwe\nor\ndays have failed.\nIn this country and in Europe are\nnow suffering more from the recent\nheavy depression in the price of spot\ncotton than in the continued slacken\ning in trade. As the price of spots, go\ndown the Jobbing trade demands con\ntinued concessions in the 'price of\nand manufactured fabrics, and\nh\nyarns\nthe mills find themselves in many in\nstances with accumulated stocks of\ngoods, manufactured from higher\npriced cotton- which they do not de\nsire to sell at prices much lower than\nexisted a few months back.\n\u25a0j* \"This is probably the first time In\nh long while that the cotton mill trade\nappeared to be in danger of serious\ndisorganization by the continued de\npression in the price of spot ootton.\nThe spinners can' bring about a\nchange for the better by, going ac\ntively in the market and bidding up\nprices on spot cotton for the balance\nof the remnant unsold, because they\n\u25a0will need every bale of spots in the\nSouth before another crop can be\nharvested. The present hand-to\nmouth policy of the mills in buying\nspot cotton is proving one of the best\nweapons tbe speculators hare to ham\nmer prices. Trade conditions are im\nproving, the unemployed are again\nbeing put to work in the industrial\ncenters of the country, and the pres\nent lull In the demand for cotton fab\nrics cannot continue much \"longer. As\nthe spinning industry gets back on\na normal footing the demand for spot\ncotton will cause prices to advance\nand the present ritt In the clouds, will\nwiden to a' noonday brightness of\ngeneral prosperity again.\"\nA W6man Tell* Mow to Relieve\nRheumatic Pain*. s\nI have neen a very great sufferer\nfrom the dreadful disease, rheumaUsm\nfor a number of years. I have tried\nmedicines but never got much\nmany\nrelelf from any of them until two year*\nago, when I bought a bottle of Cham\nberlains' Pain Balm. I found relief\nbefore I had used all of one bottle,\nand kept on applying It and soon felt\nlike a different woman. Through my\nadvice many of my women friends\nhave tried it and can tell you how\nwonderfully it has worked.\u2014-Mr*. Sar\na